text: The first movie was good just because it was a new concept.  I don't mean in the found footage sense (yes, pedants, I'm aware that Blair Witch didn't invent the genre), but just in the way it was put together as a whole.  The whole, low-budget, ad-libbed. aspect of it made it an interesting watch.  I didn't find it scary, but I want to give the creators props for trying something different and succeeding.  But this sequel... I don't know.  I know that trailers can sometimes undersell a movie but from the look of it, this just looks like the first movie with different actors.  Blair Witch wasn't scary but it was new.  This sequel seems to be neither scary nor new.

text: The problem with the original Blair Witch is that it got over-hyped. It was quite original when it was released and one of the very first in the "found footage" genre. It was a great delight for those who went into it knowing very little, but it got TOO big and once the theaters filled up it just wasn't able to deliver on the expectations. The film would very likely be a cult-classic had it not sky-rocketed in popularity so quickly. People expected a lot more when they went to see it and ended up walking out frustrated and wondering what they just paid to watch. But yes, it made a lot of money for such a small film, too, and I believe that's why the studios have been trying to cash in on that original and magical concept. No idea how this film will be, but hey, worth a shot I guess. FWIW, the concept of a witch in the woods is pretty scary.

text: This looks disappointing.  The original Blair Witch came out in the early days of the internet. Only a small percentage of people had the internet, and it was an indie film, so people didn't know for sure it was fake.   It was being marketed as found footage, and they started a grass roots campaign to make people think it was real. The campaign was pretty effective early on. By the time the film was bought by a major production company and hit mass release, the gag was out.  The fact that it didn't have special effects made it seem real. The fact that there wasn't anything visibly super natural made people think it was real. By the time it was known to be a hoax, then people ragged on the lack of those things, but that's what made the hoax believable.  I saw the original in an early screening before the gag was out. People in the theater were truly frightened; I mean REALLY scared. It was a very cool experience that I don't think movie goers in the post internet age will ever experience again.  The internet is a wonderful thing, but I also miss the world that was full of mystery, before you could just google it. For those of you born into a world with the internet, you missed that. There is something to be said for a world of mystery and the unknown.
